= The Lipid Bilayer

== Overview: The General Structure of Cell Membranes
- All biological membranes share a common general structure: a very thin film of lipid and protein molecules held together mainly by noncovalent interactions (Figure 10-1).
- The *lipid bilayer* (脂双层) is about 5 nm thick and provides the basic fluid, impermeable structure of the membrane; it is an essentially impermeable barrier to most water-soluble molecules.
- *Membrane proteins* (膜蛋白) perform most of the specific functions of membranes—transport, catalysis, signal reception, structural linkage—and it is estimated that about 30% of the proteins encoded in an animal's genome are membrane proteins.
- Cell membranes are dynamic, fluid structures; most molecules are free to move laterally within the plane of the membrane.

== Glycerophospholipids, Sphingolipids, and Sterols Are the Major Lipids in Cell Membranes
- Lipid molecules constitute about 50% of the mass of most animal cell membranes (the remainder being protein), with roughly 50 lipid molecules for every protein molecule.
- All membrane lipids are *amphiphilic* (两亲性的): they have a hydrophilic ("water-loving") polar head and a hydrophobic ("water-fearing") nonpolar tail, which drives their spontaneous assembly into bilayers.
- *Phospholipids* (磷脂) are the most abundant membrane lipids. They have a polar head group (containing phosphate) and two hydrophobic hydrocarbon tails (usually fatty acids of 14–24 carbons).
  - *Glycerophospholipids* (甘油磷脂) have a three-carbon glycerol backbone; major examples include phosphatidylcholine, phosphatidylethanolamine, and phosphatidylserine (Figure 10-2, 10-3A–C).
  - *Sphingolipids* (鞘脂) are built from sphingosine rather than glycerol. *Sphingomyelin* (鞘磷脂), the most common, has a fatty acid tail and a phosphocholine head group (Figure 10-3D, E).
  - Only *phosphatidylserine* (磷脂酰丝氨酸) carries a net negative charge; the others are electrically neutral at physiological pH.
- *Cholesterol* (胆固醇) is a major *sterol* (固醇) in animal cell membranes. Its rigid, planar steroid ring structure inserts with its single hydroxyl group near the polar head groups of phospholipids, stiffening the hydrocarbon chain region nearest the head groups (Figure 10-4, 10-5).
- *Glycolipids* (糖脂) have sugar groups as their head group instead of phosphate. In animal cells they are derived from sphingosine and are found exclusively on the outer (extracellular) leaflet of the plasma membrane (Figure 10-3 context, 10-16).
- Different biological membranes differ markedly in lipid composition (Table 10-1): bacterial membranes often have one main phospholipid and no cholesterol; eukaryotic plasma membranes contain large amounts of sterols and a mixture of hundreds to thousands of different lipid species.

== Phospholipids Spontaneously Form Bilayers
- In water, *hydrophilic* (亲水性) molecules interact favorably with water via hydrogen bonds and electrostatic interactions. *Hydrophobic* (疏水性) molecules force surrounding water into ordered "icelike cage" structures, increasing free energy—this is the entropic *hydrophobic effect* (疏水效应) (Figure 10-6).
- When phospholipids are exposed to water, the hydrophobic effect drives them to aggregate. Depending on their shape, they form either *micelles* (胶束)—spherical aggregates with tails inward (cone-shaped lipids)—or bilayers (cylinder-shaped phospholipids) (Figure 10-7).
- The lipid bilayer has a *self-sealing* (自封合) property: any free edge is energetically unfavorable (hydrophobic tails exposed to water), so the bilayer spontaneously closes into a sealed compartment—the fundamental basis of the living cell (Figure 10-8).
- *Liposomes* (脂质体) are spherical vesicles made from pure phospholipids; they are used as model membranes in experimental studies (Figure 10-9).

== The Lipid Bilayer Is a Two-dimensional Fluid
- Individual lipid molecules can diffuse freely *laterally* within their own monolayer (D ≈ 10⁻⁸ cm²/sec), allowing them to traverse the length of a bacterial cell in ~1 second.
- Lipid molecules also rotate rapidly about their long axis and have flexible hydrocarbon chains; this disordered structure is captured in computer simulations (Figure 10-10).
- *Flip-flop* (翻转) of a phospholipid from one leaflet to the other is extremely rare (time scale of hours) because the hydrophilic head group must pass through the hydrophobic core. Cholesterol is an exception and can flip-flop rapidly.
- In biological membranes, *phospholipid translocators* (磷脂转位酶)—flippases and scramblases—catalyze flip-flop to equilibrate newly synthesized lipids (made in the cytosolic leaflet of the ER) to both leaflets, maintaining proper membrane growth.
- Liposomes do not spontaneously fuse because their hydrated surfaces prevent close approach; all biological membrane fusion events are catalyzed by tethers and fusion proteins.

== The Fluidity of a Lipid Bilayer Depends on Its Composition
- Membrane fluidity is critical: certain transport processes and enzyme activities cease when bilayer viscosity exceeds a threshold. Fluidity is affected by:
  - *Fatty acid chain length*: shorter chains reduce hydrocarbon tail interactions and keep the membrane fluid at lower temperatures.
  - *Degree of unsaturation*: *cis-double bonds* (顺式双键) create kinks in hydrocarbon chains, preventing tight packing and maintaining fluidity (Figure 10-11). Bacteria adjust fatty acid composition in response to temperature changes.
  - *Cholesterol content*: cholesterol has a dual role—it stiffens chains near the head groups (decreasing permeability to small molecules) yet prevents crystallization by disrupting chain packing. Its net effect is to modulate fluidity.
- A *phase transition* (相变) from the liquid to the gel (crystalline) state occurs at a characteristic temperature that is lower for lipids with shorter or unsaturated chains.
- Eukaryotic membranes contain a bewildering variety of perhaps 500–2000 different lipid species; this *lipid heterogeneity* (脂质异质性) helps prevent large-scale phase transitions and allows membrane-spanning proteins to fit better in the bilayer.

== Lipid Bilayers Can Form Domains of Different Compositions
- Although a bilayer is a two-dimensional fluid, lipids can segregate into specialized domains. In artificial bilayers, certain lipid mixtures undergo lateral phase separation into distinct domains of different composition (Figure 10-12).
- In living cell membranes, *lipid rafts* (脂筏) are specialized, transient membrane microdomains enriched in cholesterol, sphingolipids, glycolipids, and GPI-anchored proteins; they form through weak protein-protein, protein-lipid, and lipid-lipid interactions (Figure 10-13). Rafts can be tiny nanoclusters or larger structures such as caveolae.
- Lipid rafts are thought to help organize membrane proteins for signaling or vesicle transport.

== Lipid Droplets Are Surrounded by a Phospholipid Monolayer
- Most eukaryotic cells store excess lipids as *lipid droplets* (脂滴). These store *neutral lipids* (中性脂质) such as triacylglycerols and cholesterol esters—exclusively hydrophobic molecules that aggregate into three-dimensional droplets.
- Lipid droplets are surrounded by a *phospholipid monolayer* (磷脂单层) (not a bilayer) with hydrophilic head groups facing the cytosol.
- They form from the ER membrane via a process involving the protein *seipin* (塞平蛋白) and associated assembly factors (Figure 10-14).

== The Asymmetry of the Lipid Bilayer Is Functionally Important
- The lipid compositions of the two leaflets differ markedly. In human red blood cells: the outer leaflet is enriched in *phosphatidylcholine* and *sphingomyelin*; the inner (cytosolic) leaflet is enriched in *phosphatidylethanolamine* and *phosphatidylserine* (Figure 10-15).
- This asymmetry is functionally important:
  - The negatively charged phosphatidylserine in the inner leaflet creates a charge difference across the bilayer and is required by enzymes like *protein kinase C* (PKC, 蛋白激酶C).
  - *Inositol phospholipids* (肌醇磷脂) concentrated in the inner leaflet are phosphorylated by lipid kinases (e.g., *PI 3-kinase*, 磷酸肌醇3-激酶) to create docking sites recruiting cytosolic signaling proteins; they are also cleaved by *phospholipase C* (磷脂酶C) to generate intracellular messengers.
  - During *apoptosis* (细胞凋亡), *phosphatidylserine* translocates to the outer leaflet—a signal for phagocytes to engulf and digest the dying cell.

== Glycolipids Are Found on the Surface of All Eukaryotic Plasma Membranes
- *Glycolipids* (糖脂) are found exclusively in the outer (noncytosolic) leaflet of all eukaryotic plasma membranes. Their sugar groups are added in the Golgi lumen and are always exposed at the cell surface.
- *Gangliosides* (神经节苷脂), the most complex glycolipids, contain oligosaccharides with one or more negatively charged *sialic acid* (唾液酸) moieties (Figure 10-16). They are especially abundant in nerve cells.
- Functions include: protecting membranes from harsh extracellular conditions; modulating the electrical field at the cell surface; participating in cell-recognition processes via *lectins* (凝集素); and acting as receptors for bacterial toxins (e.g., cholera toxin binds GM1) and viruses (e.g., influenza uses sialic acid).

= Membrane Proteins

== Membrane Proteins Can Be Associated with the Lipid Bilayer in Various Ways
- Membrane proteins are classified by how they associate with the bilayer (Figure 10-17):
  1. *Single-pass transmembrane proteins* (单次跨膜蛋白): the polypeptide crosses the bilayer once as an α helix.
  2. *Multipass transmembrane proteins* (多次跨膜蛋白): the polypeptide crosses multiple times as α helices (example 2) or as a β barrel (example 5).
  3. Proteins anchored to the cytosolic surface by an *amphiphilic α helix* (两亲性α螺旋) (example 6) or by a covalently attached lipid chain (example 7).
  4. Proteins attached to the extracellular surface by a *GPI anchor* (糖基磷脂酰肌醇锚, GPI锚) (example 8).
  5. *Peripheral membrane proteins* (外周膜蛋白): bound to either face by noncovalent interactions with other membrane proteins (examples 9, 10); released by high/low ionic strength or extreme pH.
- Only transmembrane proteins can function on both sides or transport molecules across the membrane.

== Lipid Anchors Control the Membrane Localization of Some Signaling Proteins
- Some signaling proteins are attached to the cytosolic leaflet by *lipid anchors* (脂质锚): *myristoyl groups* (肉豆蔻酰基) attached via amide linkage to N-terminal glycine; *palmitoyl groups* (棕榈酰基) attached via thioester linkage to cysteine; and *farnesyl/geranylgeranyl prenyl groups* (法尼酰基/牛儿牛儿酰基) attached via thioether linkage to cysteine (Figure 10-18).
- Src-family kinases are myristoylated and palmitoylated; Ras GTPases use prenyl plus palmitoyl anchors to associate with the plasma membrane.
- Single lipid anchors provide weak membrane attachment; a second anchor is often added to anchor proteins more firmly.
- Many Rab GTPases switch between membrane-bound (GTP state, anchor exposed) and cytosolic (GDP state, bound to GDI) forms, enabling dynamic regulation of membrane association.

== In Most Transmembrane Proteins, the Polypeptide Chain Crosses the Lipid Bilayer in an α-Helical Conformation
- In the hydrophobic interior of the bilayer, all peptide bonds are driven to hydrogen-bond with one another (no water available). The most common solution is to form an *α helix* (α螺旋) as the chain crosses the bilayer (Figure 10-19).
- *Single-pass proteins* cross once; *multipass proteins* cross multiple times.
- Membrane-spanning α helices typically contain 20–30 amino acids, predominantly hydrophobic. They can be identified in *hydropathy plots* (疏水性分析图), which graph the hydrophobicity index versus position in the sequence (Figure 10-20).
  - Glycophorin has one peak (single transmembrane helix).
  - Bacteriorhodopsin has seven peaks (seven transmembrane helices).
- About 30% of an organism's proteins are estimated to be transmembrane proteins.
- Some multipass proteins contain short helices that penetrate only partway through the bilayer (e.g., in aquaporin water channels, Figure 10-21); these cannot be identified from hydropathy plots alone.

== Transmembrane α Helices Often Interact with One Another
- In multipass membrane proteins, adjacent transmembrane helices pack together in specific positions, burying polar and charged residues at their interfaces rather than exposing them to the hydrophobic lipid core (Figure 10-22).
- This arrangement allows multipass proteins to create *hydrophilic pathways* (亲水通道) across the bilayer for ions and small water-soluble molecules, explaining the functional diversity of channels, transporters, and receptors.
- Even in single-pass proteins, transmembrane helices can mediate specific protein-protein interactions (e.g., glycophorin homodimerization is driven entirely by transmembrane domain interactions).

== Some β Barrels Form Large Channels
- An alternative way for polypeptide bonds to maximize hydrogen-bonding in the bilayer is to form a *β barrel* (β桶): multiple β strands arranged as a cylinder with all edge hydrogen bonds satisfied (Figure 10-23).
- All β-barrel membrane proteins share this architecture: outside of cylinder is hydrophobic (faces lipid), interior varies (can be open channel or plugged).
- β barrels range from 8 to 22 strands and are abundant in the outer membranes of bacteria, mitochondria, and chloroplasts.
- Key examples:
  - *OmpA* (8-stranded): virus receptor with a rigid barrel anchor.
  - *OMPLA* (12-stranded): lipase enzyme with catalytic residues projecting from the barrel surface.
  - *Porin* (16-stranded): water-filled channel selective for small hydrophilic molecules; loops narrow the lumen for selectivity.
  - *FepA* (22-stranded): iron transporter with a large globular plug domain inside the barrel that binds iron and undergoes conformational changes to transfer it.
- Unlike α-helical bundles, β-barrel strands are rigidly hydrogen-bonded to neighbors, making β barrels remarkably stable and among the first multipass proteins to have their structures determined.

== Many Membrane Proteins Are Glycosylated
- Most transmembrane proteins in animal cells are *glycosylated* (糖基化): sugar residues are added in the ER lumen and Golgi apparatus, so oligosaccharide chains are always on the noncytosolic side of the membrane (Figure 10-24).
- The extracellular reducing environment differs from the cytosol: disulfide (S–S) bonds form on the noncytosolic side but not in the reducing cytosol.
- Together, glycoproteins and glycolipids form the *glycocalyx* (糖萼) or cell coat—a carbohydrate-rich layer on the extracellular surface of all eukaryotic cells (Figure 10-25).
- Functions of the glycocalyx: protects cells from mechanical and chemical damage; keeps foreign cells at a distance; mediates cell-recognition via lectins.
- Oligosaccharide chains are enormously diverse (branched, varied linkages) and are especially well suited for specific cell-recognition processes (e.g., lymphocyte recirculation, inflammatory responses).

== Membrane Proteins Can Be Solubilized and Purified in Detergents
- *Detergents* (去垢剂) are small amphiphilic molecules that disrupt the lipid bilayer and bring membrane proteins into solution. They form *micelles* (胶束) above a characteristic *critical micelle concentration* (CMC, 临界胶束浓度) (Figure 10-26).
- Detergents can be ionic (e.g., *SDS*, sodium dodecyl sulfate) or nonionic (e.g., *Triton X-100*, *β-octylglucoside*).
  - *SDS* is a strong ionic detergent that solubilizes and denatures membrane proteins; useful for SDS-PAGE analysis but destroys activity.
  - *Mild nonionic detergents* (e.g., Triton X-100) solubilize membrane proteins without unfolding them; the protein is isolated as a protein-lipid-detergent complex (Figure 10-27).
- Purified membrane proteins can be *reconstituted* (重建) into liposomes by removing detergent in the presence of excess phospholipid, restoring functional activity (e.g., the Na⁺-K⁺ pump; Figure 10-28).
- Membrane proteins can also be reconstituted into *nanodiscs* (纳米盘)—small lipid patches encircled by an HDL-derived belt protein—for structural studies by cryo-EM (Figure 10-29).

== Bacteriorhodopsin: A Light-driven Proton Pump with Seven Transmembrane α Helices
- *Bacteriorhodopsin* (细菌视紫红质) is found in the "purple membrane" patches of the archaeon *Halobacterium salinarum* (盐生嗜盐菌). It forms tightly packed two-dimensional crystalline arrays that facilitated early structure determination (Figure 10-30).
- Each bacteriorhodopsin molecule contains seven closely packed transmembrane α helices and one *retinal* (视黄醛) chromophore (the aldehyde form of vitamin A), covalently linked to a lysine side chain.
- Mechanism: a single photon activates retinal, triggering conformational changes that transfer one H⁺ from inside to outside the cell via a series of proton transfers through hydrophilic residues lining a path through the protein (Figure 10-31A).
- In bright light, each molecule pumps several hundred H⁺/second. The resulting H⁺ gradient drives ATP synthesis and other energy-requiring processes.
- The crystal structure reveals tightly bound lipid molecules on the protein surface (Figure 10-31B), illustrating that specific lipid-protein interactions help stabilize membrane proteins.
- Bacteriorhodopsin is the prototype of the large superfamily of *seven-transmembrane helix proteins* (七次跨膜蛋白), which includes *G-protein-coupled receptors* (GPCRs, G蛋白偶联受体) and channelrhodopsins.

== Membrane Proteins Often Function as Large Complexes
- Many membrane proteins function as multicomponent complexes (e.g., the bacterial photosynthetic reaction center, photosystem II with 19 subunits and >60 transmembrane helices).
- Membrane protein complexes are involved in energy harvesting (photosynthesis), proton pumping, electron transport, and signal transduction.

== Many Membrane Proteins Diffuse in the Plane of the Membrane
- Like lipids, membrane proteins do not flip-flop across the bilayer (prohibitively high energy barrier), but they can rotate about an axis perpendicular to the membrane and diffuse laterally.
- The classic *mouse-human cell fusion experiment* (小鼠-人细胞融合实验) demonstrated lateral diffusion: mouse and human plasma membrane proteins initially separated but intermixed over the entire surface within ~30 minutes (Figure 10-32).
- *FRAP* (*fluorescence recovery after photobleaching*, 光漂白后荧光恢复) measures lateral diffusion rates: a laser bleaches fluorescent molecules in a small membrane area, and the rate of fluorescence recovery as unbleached molecules diffuse in yields the diffusion coefficient (Figure 10-33).
  - Diffusion coefficients vary widely among proteins due to interactions with other proteins.
  - Minimally impeded proteins give values suggesting membrane viscosity comparable to olive oil.
- *Single-particle tracking* (单粒子追踪) labels individual molecules (antibody-fluorophore or gold particles) and tracks their paths by video microscopy, revealing confinement within small membrane domains (corrals).

== Cells Can Confine Proteins and Lipids to Specific Domains Within a Membrane
- Cells can restrict membrane proteins to specific regions:
  - Epithelial cells confine certain proteins to the *apical* (顶端) surface and others to the *basal/lateral* (基底/侧面) surfaces; tight junctions prevent intermixing of both proteins and outer leaflet lipids (Figure 10-34).
  - Guinea pig sperm plasma membrane has at least three distinct protein domains (anterior head, posterior head, tail) separated by molecular fences (Figure 10-35).
- Four mechanisms restrict protein lateral mobility (Figure 10-36):
  1. Self-assembly into large aggregates (e.g., bacteriorhodopsin two-dimensional crystals).
  2. Tethering to extracellular macromolecular assemblies.
  3. Tethering to intracellular cytoskeletal assemblies.
  4. Interaction with proteins on adjacent cells.

== The Cortical Cytoskeleton Gives Membranes Mechanical Strength and Restricts Membrane Protein Diffusion
- The characteristic biconcave shape of red blood cells (Figure 10-37) is maintained by an underlying *spectrin* (血影蛋白)-based cytoskeleton.
- *Spectrin* is a long (~100 nm), flexible, heterodimeric protein. Spectrin tetramers form a netlike meshwork on the cytosolic surface of the red blood cell membrane, linked at *junctional complexes* containing short actin filaments, band 4.1, and adducin (Figure 10-38).
- The cytoskeleton is attached to the membrane through:
  - *Band 3* (多次跨膜蛋白 band 3) + *ankyrin* (锚蛋白) binding spectrin.
  - *Glycophorin* (血型糖蛋白) + *band 4.1* binding spectrin.
- Genetic abnormalities in spectrin cause *hemolytic anemia* (溶血性贫血) with spherical, fragile red blood cells.
- In nucleated cells, an analogous but more dynamic *cortical actin network* (皮质肌动蛋白网络) underlies the plasma membrane, controlling cell shape, endocytosis, and movement.
- The cortical cytoskeleton forms mechanical barriers that partition the membrane into small *corrals* (小围栏) (Figure 10-39). Proteins diffuse rapidly within corrals but only rarely escape to adjacent corrals when cytoskeletal filaments transiently detach.
- Large cytoplasmic domains make transmembrane proteins harder to pass through cytoskeletal barriers; receptor activation, which builds up large cytosolic complexes, further confines receptors to corrals to concentrate signaling complexes.

== Membrane-bending Proteins Deform Bilayers
- Cell membranes assume many shapes (flat sheets, tubules, vesicles, fenestrated sheets, cisternae). *Membrane-bending proteins* (膜弯曲蛋白) control local membrane curvature, often working together with cytoskeletal dynamics.
- Three principal mechanisms of membrane bending (Figure 10-40):
  1. *Hydrophobic wedge insertion* (疏水楔插入): amphiphilic helices or hydrophobic hairpins insert into one monolayer, increasing its area and causing bending (e.g., ER tubule-shaping proteins).
  2. *Rigid scaffold formation* (刚性支架形成): proteins form curved scaffolds that deform or stabilize a curved membrane (e.g., coat proteins on transport vesicles).
  3. *Lipid clustering* (脂质聚集): proteins cluster cone-shaped lipids (e.g., phosphoinositides with large head groups) in one leaflet, inducing *positive curvature* (正曲率); removing head groups produces inversely shaped lipids that induce *negative curvature* (负曲率).
- Multiple membrane-bending proteins collaborate to achieve particular curvatures, as in shaping budding transport vesicles.
